VALUES
(43, 19, 1, 23, 53, 5, 5, 'scourged him', 'Connection of Suffering and Healing', 'This connection highlights the theme of suffering in both passages. John 19:1 mentions Jesus being scourged, while Isaiah 53:5 speaks of being wounded and bruised, emphasizing the physical suffering that leads to healing.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 1, 23, 50, 6, 6, 'scourged him', 'Connection of Suffering and Scourging', 'This connection highlights the theme of suffering endured by Jesus. Both passages emphasize physical abuse, with John mentioning Jesus being scourged and Isaiah referring to giving his back to the smiters.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 1, 40, 20, 19, 19, NULL, 'Connection of Scourging in Passages', 'Both passages emphasize the act of scourging Jesus, highlighting the suffering he endured before his crucifixion. This connection illustrates the fulfillment of the prophecy regarding his treatment by the Gentiles.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 1, 42, 18, 33, 33, 'scourged him', 'Connection of Scourging and Death', 'This connection highlights the theme of suffering in both passages. John 19:1 describes Jesus being scourged, while Luke 18:33 predicts that he will be scourged and put to death.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 1, 42, 23, 16, 16, 'scourged him', 'Connection of Scourging and Chastisement', 'This connection highlights the theme of punishment, as both passages refer to the physical suffering of Jesus. The term ''scourged'' in John 19:1 parallels ''chastise'' in Luke 23:16, indicating a shared focus on the act of inflicting pain.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 1, 19, 129, 3, 3, 'scourged him', 'Connection of Suffering Imagery', 'This connection highlights the theme of physical suffering. Both passages emphasize the brutal treatment of the body, with ''scourged'' in John paralleling the imagery of ''plowed upon my back'' in Psalms.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 1, 40, 23, 34, 34, 'scourged him', 'Connection of Scourging and Persecution', 'This connection highlights the theme of suffering inflicted on individuals. Both passages emphasize the act of scourging, linking Jesus'' suffering to the persecution of prophets.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 2, 41, 15, 16, 20, 'crown of thorns', 'Mocking of Jesus by Soldiers', 'Both passages emphasize the soldiers'' actions of mocking Jesus by placing a crown of thorns on his head and dressing him in purple. This connection highlights the humiliation he faced during his trial and crucifixion.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 2, 19, 22, 6, 6, NULL, 'Connection of Reproach and Suffering', 'This connection highlights the theme of humiliation and suffering. Both passages emphasize the scorn faced by the figures, with John depicting Jesus as a mocked king and Psalms expressing deep personal reproach.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 2, 23, 53, 3, 3, NULL, 'Connection of Suffering and Rejection', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of suffering and rejection. The ''crown of thorns'' in John symbolizes the mockery and pain faced by Jesus, aligning with Isaiah''s description of being ''despised and rejected of men.''', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 2, 40, 27, 27, 31, 'crown of thorns', 'Connection of Mocking and Robe', 'Both passages emphasize the soldiers'' actions of mocking Jesus and dressing him in a robe. The crown of thorns is a shared detail, highlighting the humiliation he faced during his trial.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 2, 42, 23, 11, 11, 'purple robe', 'Mocking of Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the mocking of Jesus through the use of robes. In John, soldiers mock Him with a purple robe, while in Luke, Herod''s men mock Him with a gorgeous robe.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 2, 23, 49, 7, 7, 'crown of thorns', 'Connection of Kings and Despised Servant', 'This connection highlights the theme of Jesus as a figure who is both despised and yet recognized by rulers. In John 19:2, the soldiers mock Jesus with a crown, while Isaiah 49:7 speaks of a servant whom nations abhor but who will ultimately be honored by kings.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 2, 43, 19, 5, 5, NULL, 'Crown of Thorns and Robe', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus wearing the crown of thorns and the purple robe, highlighting his mockery and suffering. The repetition of these elements underscores the humiliation he faced before his crucifixion.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 3, 40, 27, 29, 29, 'Hail, King of the Jews!', 'Mockery of Jesus'' Kingship', 'Both passages emphasize the mocking of Jesus as ''King of the Jews.'' The actions of smiting and crowning with thorns illustrate the scorn he faced during his crucifixion.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 3, 40, 26, 49, 49, 'Hail, King of the Jews!', 'Connection of Salutation and Mockery', 'Both passages emphasize the phrase ''Hail,'' used in a context of greeting. In John, it is a mocking salutation to Jesus as ''King,'' while in Matthew, it is a respectful greeting from Judas. This connection highlights the contrasting attitudes towards Jesus.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 3, 42, 1, 28, 28, 'Hail', 'Contrasting Greetings of Kingship', 'This connection highlights the contrasting uses of ''Hail'' in both passages. In John, it is a mocking salute to Jesus as ''King of the Jews,'' while in Luke, it is a genuine greeting to Mary, acknowledging her favor and blessing.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 3, 43, 18, 33, 33, 'King of the Jews', 'Connection Between Kingship References', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' identity as ''King of the Jews.'' In John 18:33, Pilate questions Jesus about this title, while in John 19:3, soldiers mockingly affirm it, highlighting the theme of Jesus'' kingship.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 3, 43, 19, 19, 22, 'King of the Jews', 'Connection of Kingship Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the title of Jesus as ''King of the Jews.'' The mockery in the first passage and the formal inscription in the second highlight the significance of this title in the narrative.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 4, 43, 18, 38, 38, 'I find no fault in him', 'Pilate''s Declaration of Innocence', 'Both passages emphasize Pilate''s assertion of Jesus'' innocence. In John 18:38, he states, ''I find in him no fault at all,'' which is reiterated in John 19:4 as ''I find no fault in him.'' This connection highlights Pilate''s consistent judgment regarding Jesus.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 4, 43, 19, 6, 6, 'I find no fault in him', 'Pilate''s Declaration of Innocence', 'Both passages emphasize Pilate''s assertion of Jesus'' innocence. In John 19:4, he states, ''I find no fault in him,'' which is reiterated in John 19:6, reinforcing his judgment.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 4, 42, 23, 4, 4, 'I find no fault in him', 'Pilate''s Declaration of Innocence', 'Both passages emphasize Pilate''s assertion of Jesus'' innocence. The phrase ''I find no fault in him'' appears in both accounts, highlighting a consistent message regarding Jesus'' lack of guilt.', 'parallel', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 4, 42, 23, 47, 47, 'find no fault in him', 'Recognition of Righteousness', 'This connection highlights the acknowledgment of Jesus'' righteousness. Pilate declares he finds no fault in him, while the centurion affirms he was a righteous man.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 4, 60, 2, 22, 22, 'I find no fault in him', 'Sinlessness of Christ', 'This connection highlights the sinlessness of Jesus in both passages. John 19:4 states Pilate finds no fault in him, while 1 Peter 2:22 affirms that he did no sin.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 4, 40, 27, 4, 4, 'no fault in him', 'Innocence of Jesus', 'This connection highlights the theme of Jesus'' innocence. In John 19:4, Pilate states he finds no fault in Jesus, while Matthew 27:4 emphasizes the betrayal of ''innocent blood.''', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 4, 40, 27, 19, 19, 'no fault in him', 'Pilate''s Judgment of Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize Pilate''s recognition of Jesus as ''just'' and without fault. Pilate''s declaration in John aligns with his wife''s warning about the ''just man'' in Matthew, highlighting a shared acknowledgment of Jesus'' innocence.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 5, 43, 19, 2, 2, 'crown of thorns, and the purple robe', 'Connection of Thorns and Robe', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus wearing a crown of thorns and a purple robe, highlighting the mockery he faced. The description in John 19:2 sets the stage for Pilate''s proclamation in John 19:5.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 5, 23, 7, 14, 14, 'Behold the man!', 'Connection of Divine Revelation', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine revelation in both passages. In John 19:5, Pilate presents Jesus as a significant figure, while Isaiah 7:14 proclaims the miraculous birth of Immanuel, indicating God''s presence among His people.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 5, 43, 1, 29, 29, 'Behold the man!', 'Behold the Man and Lamb', 'This connection highlights the presentation of Jesus in both passages. In John 19:5, Pilate''s declaration, ''Behold the man!'' contrasts with John 1:29''s ''Behold the Lamb of God,'' emphasizing Jesus'' dual role as both the suffering servant and sacrificial lamb.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 5, 58, 12, 2, 2, 'Behold the man!', 'Connection Between Jesus'' Suffering and Faith', 'This connection highlights Jesus'' endurance through suffering, as seen in both passages. In John 19:5, Jesus is presented in a state of humiliation, while Hebrews 12:2 emphasizes his perseverance for the joy set before him.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 5, 23, 40, 9, 9, 'Behold the man!', 'Connection of Divine Revelation', 'This connection highlights the proclamation of Jesus as the embodiment of God''s presence, as seen in Pilate''s declaration ''Behold the man!'' and the call in Isaiah to ''Behold your God!'' Both passages emphasize the revelation of divine authority and presence to the people.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 5, 25, 1, 12, 12, NULL, 'Sorrow and Affliction Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of suffering and sorrow. Both passages emphasize the visible state of Jesus and the lament of affliction, inviting observers to witness the depth of his pain.', 'theme', 0.293, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 6, 43, 18, 31, 31, NULL, 'Judgment and Authority in Trials', 'Both passages emphasize Pilate''s authority in the trial of Jesus. In John 18:31, Pilate tells the Jews to judge Jesus according to their law, while in John 19:6, he asserts he finds no fault in him, highlighting the tension between Roman and Jewish legal authority.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 6, 43, 19, 4, 4, 'for I find no fault in him', 'Pilate''s Declaration of Innocence', 'Both passages emphasize Pilate''s assertion of Jesus'' innocence. In John 19:4, Pilate states, ''I find no fault in him,'' which is reiterated in John 19:6 when he tells the chief priests to crucify Jesus despite this finding.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 6, 40, 27, 22, 22, NULL, 'Pilate''s Role in the Crucifixion', 'Both passages emphasize Pilate''s questioning of the crowd regarding Jesus'' fate. In each instance, the crowd demands crucifixion, highlighting their collective decision against Jesus.', 'parallel', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 6, 41, 15, 12, 15, 'for I find no fault in him', 'Pilate''s Reluctance to Condemn', 'Both passages emphasize Pilate''s declaration of Jesus'' innocence, as he states, ''I find no fault in him'' in John and questions, ''What evil hath he done?'' in Mark. This connection highlights Pilate''s struggle against the crowd''s demand for crucifixion.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 6, 42, 23, 4, 4, 'for I find no fault in him', 'Pilate''s Declaration of Innocence', 'Both passages emphasize Pilate''s assertion of Jesus'' innocence. In both instances, Pilate explicitly states, ''I find no fault in him.'' This connection highlights the consistency of Pilate''s judgment regarding Jesus.', 'parallel', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 6, 44, 2, 23, 23, 'Crucify him, crucify him', 'Connection of Crucifixion Events', 'This connection highlights the theme of crucifixion in both passages. John 19:6 describes the act of crucifixion, while Acts 2:23 refers to it as an act carried out by wicked hands, emphasizing the culpability of those involved.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 6, 44, 3, 13, 15, 'Crucify him, crucify him', 'Connection Between Jesus'' Trial and Death', 'Both passages emphasize the rejection of Jesus by the people and their choice to crucify him. In John 19:6, Pilate finds no fault in Jesus, while Acts 3:13-15 highlights that the people delivered him up and desired a murderer instead.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 7, 3, 24, 16, 16, 'he ought to die', 'Connection of Blasphemy and Death', 'Both passages emphasize the consequence of blasphemy against God. In John 19:7, the Jews cite their law regarding the death penalty for someone claiming to be the Son of God, paralleling Leviticus 24:16, which prescribes death for blaspheming the name of the Lord.', 'theme', 0.398, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 7, 43, 5, 18, 18, 'made himself the Son of God', 'Claims of Divine Sonship', 'Both passages emphasize the claim of Jesus as the Son of God, which incites hostility from the Jews. In John 19:7, the Jews assert that he ought to die for making himself the Son of God, while in John 5:18, they seek to kill him for claiming God as his Father, equating himself with God.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 7, 40, 26, 63, 66, 'he made himself the Son of God', 'Connection of Blasphemy and Death', 'Both passages emphasize the accusation of blasphemy against Jesus for claiming to be the Son of God, leading to a verdict of death. In John, the Jews assert that he ought to die for making himself the Son of God, while in Matthew, the high priest declares Jesus guilty of blasphemy for the same claim.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 7, 40, 27, 42, 43, 'Son of God', 'Connection of Sonship Claims', 'Both passages emphasize the claim of Jesus as the ''Son of God.'' In John, the Jews assert that he ought to die for this claim, while in Matthew, the mockers challenge his identity as the ''Son of God'' while he is on the cross.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 7, 45, 1, 4, 4, 'Son of God', 'Connection of Sonship', 'This connection highlights the theme of Jesus'' identity as the Son of God. In John 19:7, the Jews assert that he ought to die for claiming this title, while Romans 1:4 affirms his divine sonship through resurrection.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 7, 41, 14, 61, 64, 'the Son of God', 'Connection of Jesus'' Identity', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' claim to divinity. In John, the Jews accuse him of making himself ''the Son of God,'' while in Mark, Jesus affirms his identity as ''the Christ, the Son of the Blessed.'' This connection highlights the legal implications of his identity in the context of blasphemy.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 7, 41, 15, 39, 39, 'the Son of God', 'Recognition of Jesus'' Divinity', 'This connection highlights the acknowledgment of Jesus as the ''Son of God'' in both passages. The Jews claim he ought to die for making this claim, while the centurion affirms it at his death.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 8, 43, 19, 13, 13, 'he was the more afraid', 'Pilate''s Fear and Judgment', 'This connection highlights Pilate''s emotional state as he transitions from fear to action. Both passages emphasize Pilate''s response to the situation surrounding Jesus, culminating in his decision to bring Jesus forth for judgment.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 8, 44, 14, 11, 19, NULL, 'Fear and Response to Divine Acts', 'This connection highlights the theme of fear in response to divine actions. In John 19:8, Pilate''s fear arises from the implications of Jesus'' identity, while in Acts 14:11-19, the people''s fear leads them to worship Paul and Barnabas as gods. Both passages emphasize the human reaction to perceived divine intervention.', 'theme', 0.307, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 9, 43, 18, 33, 33, 'Whence art thou?', 'Pilate''s Inquiry of Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize Pilate''s questioning of Jesus. In John 18:33, Pilate asks if Jesus is the King of the Jews, while in John 19:9, he seeks to know Jesus'' origin, highlighting the ongoing interrogation.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 9, 7, 13, 6, 6, 'whence art thou', 'Silence and Inquiry', 'This connection highlights the theme of unanswered questions. In both passages, there is a moment of inquiry about identity, with Jesus remaining silent and the woman not asking the man''s origin. This reflects a shared motif of mystery surrounding divine encounters.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 9, 19, 38, 13, 15, 'But Jesus gave him no answer', 'Silence and Hope in Suffering', 'Both passages emphasize a state of silence in the face of suffering. In John 19:9, Jesus remains silent when questioned, while Psalms 38:13-15 reflects a similar silence, portraying a hope in God despite being unheard.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 9, 23, 53, 7, 7, NULL, 'Silence in Suffering', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of silence in the face of oppression. Jesus'' refusal to answer in John 19:9 parallels the description of the silent suffering servant in Isaiah 53:7.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 9, 40, 26, 63, 63, NULL, 'Silence of Jesus in Trials', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' silence during questioning. In John, He gives no answer, while in Matthew, He holds His peace, highlighting a consistent theme of His restrained response in the face of interrogation.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 9, 40, 27, 12, 14, NULL, 'Silence of Jesus Before Accusers', 'This connection highlights the theme of Jesus'' silence in the face of accusations. Both passages depict Jesus not responding to questions posed by Pilate, emphasizing his composure during the trial.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 9, 41, 15, 3, 5, NULL, 'Silence of Jesus Before Accusations', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' silence in response to questioning. In John, Pilate asks, ''Whence art thou?'' and receives no answer, while in Mark, Pilate notes that Jesus ''answered nothing'' to many accusations. This connection highlights the theme of Jesus'' passive demeanor during his trial.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 10, 27, 3, 14, 15, 'have power to crucify thee', 'Authority and Power in Trials', 'This connection highlights the theme of authority in both passages, where Pilate asserts his power over Jesus, paralleling Nebuchadnezzar''s declaration of power over Shadrach, Meshach, and Abed-nego. Both figures challenge the faith of the accused by emphasizing their ability to execute judgment.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 10, 27, 5, 19, 19, 'have power to crucify thee', 'Authority and Power in Judgment', 'This connection highlights the theme of authority in judgment. Both passages emphasize the power to decide life and death, as seen in Pilate''s claim of power to crucify or release, paralleling the authority of the king in Daniel to slay or spare.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 10, 43, 18, 39, 39, 'power to release thee', 'Power and Release Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of release, with Pilate asserting his power to release Jesus in John 19:10 and referencing the custom of releasing a prisoner in John 18:39. This connection highlights the tension between Pilate''s authority and the people''s choice regarding Jesus.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 11, 45, 13, 1, 1, NULL, 'Authority and Divine Power', 'This connection highlights the theme of power being ordained by God. Both passages emphasize that any authority held by individuals is ultimately granted by a higher power.', 'theme', 0.43299999999999994, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 11, 43, 3, 27, 27, 'except it were given thee from above', 'Divine Authority and Power', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine authority in both passages. John 19:11 emphasizes that power is granted from above, while John 3:27 states that a man can receive nothing except it be given him from heaven.', 'theme', 0.40499999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 11, 44, 2, 23, 23, 'delivered me unto thee', 'Divine Authority and Human Action', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of being delivered into human hands, highlighting the interplay between divine authority and human actions in the crucifixion of Jesus. John 19:11 speaks of power given from above, while Acts 2:23 mentions being delivered by God''s foreknowledge.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 11, 27, 4, 17, 17, 'except it were given thee from above', 'Divine Authority in Governance', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine authority over human power. Both passages emphasize that power is granted by a higher authority, with John 19:11 stating that power is given from above, and Daniel 4:17 declaring that the Most High rules in the kingdom of men.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 11, 43, 7, 30, 30, 'no power at all against me', 'Authority and Timing in Jesus'' Arrest', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine authority over human actions. In both passages, Jesus indicates that events unfold according to God''s timing and plan, as seen in ''no man laid hands on him'' and ''no power at all against me''.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 11, 44, 3, 13, 13, 'delivered me unto thee', 'Authority and Responsibility in Betrayal', 'This connection highlights the theme of accountability in betrayal. In John 19:11, Jesus indicates that those who deliver him bear greater sin, while Acts 3:13 references the act of delivering Jesus up and denying him, emphasizing the responsibility of those involved.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 11, 27, 4, 25, 25, 'power at all against me, except it were given thee from above', 'Divine Authority and Accountability', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine authority in both passages. John 19:11 emphasizes that power is granted from above, while Daniel 4:25 illustrates that the Most High rules over kingdoms, indicating accountability to divine sovereignty.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 12, 43, 18, 33, 36, 'maketh himself a king', 'Kingship and Authority', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of kingship, with Pilate questioning Jesus about being ''the King of the Jews'' and the Jews asserting that Jesus'' claim to kingship opposes Caesar. This connection highlights the tension between earthly authority and Jesus'' declaration that ''my kingdom is not of this world.''', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 12, 44, 17, 6, 7, 'whosoever maketh himself a king', 'Kingship and Allegiance to Caesar', 'This connection highlights the theme of kingship and loyalty to Caesar. Both passages address the implications of declaring Jesus as king, which challenges Roman authority.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 12, 41, 6, 16, 26, 'maketh himself a king speaketh against Cesar', 'Authority and Kingship', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of authority and the consequences of challenging it. In John 19:12, the Jews assert that releasing Jesus would oppose Caesar''s authority, while in Mark 6:16-26, Herod''s fear of losing his authority leads to the beheading of John the Baptist.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 12, 42, 23, 2, 5, 'whosoever maketh himself a king', 'Accusations Against Jesus', 'This connection highlights the accusations made against Jesus in both passages. In John, the Jews claim that Jesus makes himself a king, while in Luke, they accuse him of forbidding tribute to Caesar and claiming kingship.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 12, 44, 24, 24, 27, 'thou art not Cesarâ€™s friend', 'Political Pressure and Justice', 'This connection highlights the theme of political pressure influencing judicial decisions. In both passages, figures in authority, Pilate and Felix, are shown to be swayed by the desires of the Jewish leaders, impacting their actions regarding Jesus and Paul, respectively.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 13, 19, 82, 5, 7, 'judgment seat', 'Judgment and Authority Themes', 'This connection highlights the theme of judgment and authority present in both passages. In John 19:13, Pilate sits in judgment, while Psalms 82:5-7 discusses the authority of those in power and their ultimate fate.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 13, 40, 27, 19, 19, 'judgment seat', 'Judgment Seat Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the moment when Pilate is seated on the judgment seat, highlighting the significance of this event in the trial of Jesus. The mention of the judgment seat in both contexts underscores the authority and decision-making role of Pilate during Jesus'' trial.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 13, 19, 58, 1, 2, NULL, 'Judgment and Righteousness Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of judgment present in both passages. In John 19:13, Pilate sits in judgment, while Psalms 58:1-2 questions the righteousness of human judgment.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 13, 20, 29, 25, 25, NULL, 'Fear and Judgment Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of fear in both passages. In John 19:13, Pilate''s judgment reflects the fear of man, while Proverbs 29:25 explicitly states that ''the fear of man bringeth a snare.''', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 13, 21, 5, 8, 8, 'judgment seat', 'Judgment and Justice Themes', 'This connection highlights the theme of judgment in both passages. John 19:13 describes Pilate''s judgment seat, while Ecclesiastes 5:8 addresses the perversion of judgment and justice.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 13, 23, 51, 12, 13, NULL, 'Fear of Oppression', 'Both passages emphasize fear of human oppressors. In John, Pilate represents earthly authority, while Isaiah questions fear of man over God. This connection highlights the contrast between divine comfort and human intimidation.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
